    <p>
      With these new restrictions on the domains,
      we now have trigonometric functions that are one-to-one and so we can define their inverse functions:
    </p>
    <p>
      \begin{mybox}[Inverse Sine] The
      <em>inverse sine function</em>
          <idx><h>Inverse sine</h></idx>
      is symbolized by
      <md>
        <mrow>y=\sin^{-1}x \amp \amp  \mbox{and means}  \amp \amp x=\sin y</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The inverse sine function is also called the
      <em>arcsine function</em>,
          <idx><h>Arcsine function</h></idx>
      and is denoted by <m>\arcsin x</m>. \end{mybox}
    </p>
    <p>
      \begin{mybox}[Inverse Cosine] The
      <em>inverse cosine function</em>
          <idx><h>Inverse cosine</h></idx>
      is symbolized by
      <md>
        <mrow>y=\cos^{-1}x \amp \amp  \mbox{and means}  \amp \amp  x=\cos y</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The inverse cosine function is also called the
      <em>arccosine function</em>,
          <idx><h>Arccosine function</h></idx>
      and is denoted by <m>\arccos x</m>. \end{mybox}
    </p>
    <p>
      \begin{mybox}[Inverse Tangent] The
      <em>inverse tangent function</em>
          <idx><h>Inverse tangent</h></idx>
      is symbolized by
      <md>
        <mrow>y=\tan^{-1}x \amp \amp  \mbox{and means}  \amp \amp  x=\tan y</mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The inverse tangent function is also called the
      <em>arctangent function</em>,
          <idx><h>Arctangent function</h></idx>
      and is denoted by <m>\arctan x</m>. \end{mybox} \begin{mybox}[Inverse Cosecant, Secant,
      and Cotangent] Inverse cosecant, inverse secant,
      and inverse cotangent functions are not as common as the other trigonometric functions so we will just summarize them and not consider any examples in this book.
      <md>
        <mrow>y=\csc^{-1}x \amp \amp  \mbox{means}  \amp \amp  x=\csc y</mrow>
        <mrow>y=\sec^{-1}x \amp \amp  \mbox{means}  \amp \amp  x=\sec y</mrow>
        <mrow>y=\cot^{-1}x \amp \amp  \mbox{means}  \amp \amp  x=\cot y</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      \end{mybox} \begin{mybox}[Domain and Range] The domain and range for each function is
    </p>
    <tabular>
      <row>
        <cell>Function</cell>
        <cell>Domain</cell>
        <cell>Range</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
        <cell></cell>
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>\sin^{-1}</m></cell>
        <cell><m>[-1,1]</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\left[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right]</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell><m>\cos^{-1}</m></cell>
        <cell><m>[-1,1]</m></cell>
        <cell><m>[0,\pi]</m></cell>
      </row>
