  <subsection>
    <title>Composition of Inverse Trigonometric Functions</title>
    <p>
      Recall (from Unit 1) that if <m>f</m> is a one-to-one function with inverse <m>f^{-1}</m>, then
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(f^{-1}(y))=y</m> for every <m>y</m> in the domain of <m>f^{-1}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f^{-1}(f(x))=x</m> for every <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      In terms of trigonometric functions,
      <m>f(f^{-1}(y))=y</m> will work for all <m>y</m> in the domain, however,
      we need to be careful when evaluating
      <m>f^{-1}(f(x))=x</m> because the domain of <m>f^{-1}</m> is restricted.
    </p>
    <p>
      \begin{mybox}[Properties of Composition of Trigonometric Functions]
      <me>
        \sin(\sin^{-1}x)=x\mbox{ when } -1\leq x\leq1
      </me>
      <me>
        \cos(\cos^{-1}x)=x\mbox{ when } -1\leq x\leq1
      </me>
      <me>
        \tan(\tan^{-1}x)=x\mbox{ when } -\infty\leq x\leq\infty
      </me>
      <me>
        \sin^{-1}(\sin x)=x\mathbf{{only} when }-\frac{\pi}{2}\leq x\leq\frac{\pi}{2}
      </me>
    </p>
    <me>
      \cos^{-1}(\cos x)=x\mathbf{{only} when }0\leq x\leq\pi
    </me>
    <me>
      \tan^{-1}(\tan x)=x\mathbf{{only} when }-\frac{\pi}{2}\lt  x\lt \frac{\pi}{2}
    </me>
    <p>
      \end{mybox} <nbsp/>
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact value of each expression
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\cos^{-1}\left(\cos\frac{\pi}{8}\right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tan(\tan^{-1}7)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sin^{-1}\left(\sin\left(-\frac{\pi}{7}\right)\right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sin^{-1}\left(\sin\frac{4\pi}{5}\right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\cos(\cos^{-1}(-0.283))</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>\frac{\pi}{8}</m> is in the interval <m>[0,\pi]</m>,
                then from the properties of compositions of inverse functions, we get
                <me>
                  \cos^{-1}\left(\cos\frac{\pi}{8}\right)=\frac{\pi}{8}
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>7</m> is in the interval <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>,
                <me>
                  \tan(\tan^{-1}7)=7
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>-\frac{\pi}{7}</m> is in the interval <m>\left[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right]</m>,
                <me>
                  \sin^{-1}\left(\sin\left(-\frac{\pi}{7}\right)\right)=-\frac{\pi}{7}
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Note that <m>\frac{5\pi}{7}</m> is not in the interval <m>\left[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right]</m>.
                In order to evaluate the expression,
                we first need to find an angle, <m>\theta</m>,
                such that <m>-\frac{\pi}{2}\leq\theta\leq\frac{\pi}{2}</m> and <m>\sin\frac{5\pi}{7}=\sin\theta</m>.
                Since <m>\frac{\pi}{2}\lt \frac{5\pi}{7}\lt \pi</m> means
                <m>\frac{5\pi}{7}</m> is in Quadrant II. Recall from <xref ref="sec_unit-circle">Section</xref>
                that our reference angle is <m>\theta=\pi-\frac{5\pi}{7}=\frac{2\pi}{7}</m>.
                <image>
                   <latex-image> <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1.15,0)--(1.15,0) node[right]{\(x\)}; \draw[<->] (0,-1.15)--(0,1.15) node[above]{\(y\)}; \draw (0,0) circle (1); \draw[line width=0.5pt,blue] (0,0) -- (129:1); \draw[line width=0.5pt,blue] (0,0) -- (51:1); \draw[-stealth, line width=1pt,magenta] (0:0.2) arc (0:129:0.2) node[midway, above,xshift=3] {\(\frac{5\pi}{7}\)}; \draw[-stealth, line width=1pt] (180:0.2) arc (180:129:0.2) node[midway, left,xshift=-1,yshift=4] {\(\frac{2\pi}{7}\)}; \draw[-stealth, line width=1pt] (0:0.4) arc (0:51:0.4) node[midway, right,xshift=-0.1] {\(\frac{2\pi}{7}\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]> </latex-image>
                </image>
                Since <m>\frac{2\pi}{7}</m> is in the interval <m>\left[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right]</m>,
                <me>
                  \sin^{-1}\left(\sin\frac{5\pi}{7}\right)=\sin^{-1}\left(\sin\frac{2\pi}{7}\right)=\frac{2\pi}{7}
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>-0.283</m> is in the interval <m>[-1,1]</m>,
                <me>
                  \cos(\cos^{-1}(-0.283))=-0.283
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      Now we will look at what happens when we need to evaluate the composition of a trigonometric function and the inverse of a different trigonometric function.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact value of
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\cos\left(\tan^{-1}\frac{4}{3}\right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sin\left(\cos^{-1}\left(-\frac{3}{8}\right)\right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>\theta</m> be an angle in the range of <m>\tan^{-1}</m>, that is,
                let <m>\theta</m> be in the interval
                <m>\left(-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\right)</m> such that <m>\theta=\tan^{-1}\frac{4}{3}</m>.
                This equation is equivalent to <m>\tan\theta=\frac{4}{3}</m>.
                Since <m>\tan\theta>0</m>,
                we know that <m>\theta</m> must be in Quadrant I <m>\left(0\lt \theta\lt \frac{\pi}{2}\right)</m>.
                Let <m>(x,y)</m> be a point on the terminal side of <m>\theta</m>,
                then by the trigonometric ratios,
                <me>
                  \tan\theta=\frac{\mbox{opposite} }{\mbox{adjacent} }=\frac{y}{x}
                </me>
                Since we have <m>\tan\theta=\frac{4}{3}</m>,
                we get <m>x=3</m> and <m>y=4</m>,
                as shown in the figure below.
                <image>
                   <latex-image> <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[->] (-0.15,0)--(3.5,0) node[right]{\(x\)}; \draw[->] (0,-0.15)--(0,4.15) node[above]{\(y\)}; \draw[dashed] (3,0) -- (3,4); \draw[line width=1pt,blue] (0,0) -- (3,4); \draw[-stealth] (0:0.75) arc (0:53.1301023542:0.75) node[midway, right,xshift=-0.1] {\(\theta\)}; \filldraw[black] (3,4) circle (2pt) node[above] {\((x,y)=(3,4)\)}; \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt,mirror},xshift=0,yshift=0](0,0) -- (3,0) node[black,midway,below,yshift=-8] {\(x=3\)}; \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt,mirror},xshift=0,yshift=0](3,0) -- (3,4) node[black,midway,right,xshift=10] {\(y=4\)}; \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt},xshift=0,yshift=0](0,0) -- (3,4) node[black,midway,left,xshift=-8,yshift=9] {\(r\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]> </latex-image>
                </image>
                Evaluating <m>\cos\left(\tan^{-1}\frac{4}{3}\right)</m> is equivalent to evaluating
                <me>
                  \cos\theta=\frac{\mbox{adjacent} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} }=\frac{3}{r}
                </me>,
                where <m>r=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=\sqrt{3^2+4^2}=\sqrt{9+16}=\sqrt{25}=5</m>.
                So,
                <me>
                  \cos\left(\tan^{-1}\frac{4}{3}\right)=\cos\theta=\frac{3}{5}
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>\theta</m> be an angle in the range of <m>\cos^{-1}</m>, that is,
                let <m>\theta</m> be in the interval
                <m>\left[0,\pi\right]</m> such that <m>\theta=\cos^{-1}\left(-\frac{3}{8}\right)</m>.
                This equation is equivalent to <m>\cos\theta=-\frac{3}{8}</m>.
                Since <m>\cos\theta\lt 0</m>,
                we know that <m>\theta</m> must be in Quadrant II <m>\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\leq\theta\leq\pi\right)</m>.
                Let <m>(x,y)</m> be a point on the terminal side of <m>\theta</m>,
                then by the trigonometric ratios,
                <me>
                  \cos\theta=\frac{\mbox{adjacent} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} }=\frac{x}{r}
                </me>
                Since we have <m>\cos\theta=-\frac{3}{8}</m>,
                we get <m>\frac{x}{r}=-\frac{3}{8}</m> which gives us either <m>x=-3</m> and <m>r=8</m> or <m>x=3</m> and <m>r=-8</m>.
                Since <m>\theta</m> is in Quadrant II, we know that <m>x</m> is negative,
                thus <m>x=-3</m> and <m>r=8</m>,
                as shown in the figure below.
                <image>
                   <latex-image> <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[->] (-3.5,0)--(1.15,0) node[right]{\(x\)}; \draw[->] (0,-0.15)--(0,8) node[above]{\(y\)}; \draw[dashed] (-3,0) -- (-3,7.4161984871); \draw[line width=1pt,blue] (0,0) -- (-3,{sqrt(55)}); \draw[-stealth] (0:0.75) arc (0:112.024312837:0.75) node[midway, right,xshift=5] {\(\theta\)}; \filldraw[black] (-3,7.4161984871) circle (2pt) node[above] {\((x,y)\)}; \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt},xshift=0,yshift=0](0,0) -- (-3,0) node[black,midway,below,yshift=-8] {\(x=-3\)}; \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt},xshift=0,yshift=0](-3,0) -- (-3,7.4161984871) node[black,midway,left,xshift=-10] {\(y\)}; \draw [decorate,decoration={brace,amplitude=10pt,mirror},xshift=0,yshift=0](0,0) -- (-3,7.4161984871) node[black,midway,right,xshift=8,yshift=7] {\(r=8\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]> </latex-image>
                </image>
                Evaluating <m>\sin\left(\cos^{-1}\left(-\frac{3}{8}\right)\right)</m> is equivalent to evaluating
                <me>
                  \sin\theta=\frac{\mbox{opposite} }{\mbox{hypotenuse} }=\frac{y}{8}
                </me>,
                where
                <md>
                  <mrow>r^2\amp =\amp x^2+y^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>8^2\amp =\amp (-3)^2+y^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>64\amp =\amp 9+y^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>y^2\amp =\amp 55</mrow>
                </md>
                Thus <m>y=\sqrt{55}</m>.
                So,
                <me>
                  \sin\left(\cos^{-1}\frac{-3}{8}\right)=\sin\theta=\frac{\sqrt{55}}{8}
                </me>
                Note this is positive since sine is positive in Quadrant II.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
